      "quotes_count": 0,
      "edited_at": null,
      "content": "<p>systemd-sysext is fantastic way to add a bit of flexibility to /usr/ in a world where /usr/ is otherwise immutable. It has various really nice benefits: it&#39;s atomic in behaviour (i.e, a sysext image is either merged in or not merged in, but never &quot;half&quot; installed), it can trivially be undone (if you remove an image from the stack it&#39;s just gone again), and the security properties are great too (i.e. offline security, signatures checked against kernel keyring).</p>",
